{"source":"Alamy","photographer":"Photofusion Picture Library / Al","altText":"Children in nursery","height":"84","credit":"Photofusion Picture Library / Al/Alamy","caption":"Children in nursery. Photograph: Photofusion Picture Library / Al/Alamy","width":"140"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/23/1390480466427/Children-in-nursery-012.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Alamy","photographer":"Photofusion Picture Library / Al","altText":"Children in nursery","height":"372","credit":"Photofusion Picture Library / Al/Alamy","caption":"Children in nursery. Photograph: Photofusion Picture Library / Al/Alamy","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"The bug of Wall Street: fools' gold","webPublicationDate":"2014-01-23T13:40:09Z","sectionName":"Money","sectionId":"money","id":"money/2014/jan/23/gold-investing-wall-street-banks-value","fields":{"standfirst":"<p>Gold never loses its lustre to some believers, but it's a terrible idea to fall in love with any commodity, and especially this one</p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-01-23T14:22:24.207Z","body":"<p>We know about the wolves of Wall Street. But what do you know about the bugs?&nbsp;</p> <p>There is a pop-eyed creature that roams the markets known as the \"gold bug\". A gold bug is someone who believes investing in gold is the answer to all the world's financial anxieties: inflation, a stock market sell-off, the size of the government defict, the prospect of the dollar losing its value.</p> <p>More than any other asset class out there, gold seems to possess the ability to get otherwise level-headed people to toss caution to the winds. Diamonds may shine more brightly; hot technology IPOs usually generate more buzz on the cocktail party circuit, at least. But gold seems to possess a unique kind of luster, one able to blind some of us to logic and common sense.</p> <p>&ldquo;There seems to be a group of true believers in the religion of gold in every generation,&rdquo; says Jack Ablin, chief investment officer at BMO Private Bank. &ldquo;They become acolytes, unable to detach themselves emotionally from gold. It can be tough, even impossible, to talk them out of owning it.&rdquo;</p> <p>That&rsquo;s true, Ablin says, even when gold has hit the skids, as it did last year,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304591604579292321014055380\">posting a 28% decline (the largest in more than 30 years)</a>.&nbsp;</p> <p>That put an end to a 12-year bull market rally, but not to the dreams of gold bugs everywhere. In their eyes, gold has lost none of its luster. In their eyes, the sell-off isn&rsquo;t simply a function of normal supply and demand factors. (To mention a few: Indian export restrictions, the absence of any inflation, a decline in interest of central banks in holding gold, or the fact that an array of alternatives that started outperforming gold handily.)</p> <p>Instead, the gold bugs believe that the fall of gold&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.zerohedge.com/news/2014-01-17/sprott-manipulation-gold-central-banks-cannot-continue-2014\">is a conspiracy.</a>&nbsp;Global central banks, some gold bugs argue, are manipulating prices and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://usawatchdog.com/what-happens-when-you-have-to-admit-the-golds-not-there-eric-sprott/\">gold will soar to set new records</a>&nbsp;this year.</p> <p>Well, there&rsquo;s at least a small chance that this may be true. And there may have been a shooter on the grassy knoll on 22 November, 1963. But that still isn&rsquo;t an argument in favor of loading up your portfolio with gold.</p> <p>And that&rsquo;s the problem: the fact that at least a small percentage of people will always shun common sense and act instead&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/business/a-gold-enthusiast-listen-to-the-head--and-history/2014/01/10/d00d6cd2-762d-11e3-b1c5-739e63e9c9a7_story.html\">based instead on a compelling narrative about why gold (or any other investment)</a>&nbsp;is the greatest idea since the wheel.&nbsp;</p> <p>This goes back to a bigger strain of conspiracy theory. The unprecedented involvement of central banks in economies worldwide in the aftermath of the 2008 financial crisis set the stage for some epic storytelling. All that central bank support &ndash; ultra-low interest rates and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/quantitative-easing\">\"quantitative easing\"</a> &ndash; would set the stage for hyperinflation and the implosion of the value of the US dollar.</p> <p>Too bad none of that has materialized.</p> <p>The result, for big gold investors, has been that faith has turned into a disaster.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.ibtimes.com/swiss-central-bank-lost-165-billion-2013-thanks-gold-1527508\">Switzerland's central bank lost billions.</a>&nbsp;Hedge fund billionaire John Paulson, who first revealed his affection for gold in 2009 when the metal had already rallied to about $1,150 an ounce from only $400 or so a decade ago, lost an estimated $300 million on his positions&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.zerohedge.com/news/2013-04-13/john-paulson-loses-over-300-million-fridays-gold-tumble\">during trading on a single day last April,</a>&nbsp;and calculating his total losses has become a kind of Wall Street parlor game.&nbsp;</p> <p>Paulson has at least&nbsp;<a href=\"http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424127887324139404579013451946980712\">slashed his exposure to gold.</a>&nbsp;Other gold bugs, however, argue that the current sell-off is a great opportunity to jump in. Goldbugs point out that In Wall Street jargon, gold has a low correlation to other types of investments &ndash; meaning it&rsquo;s likely to zig when other investments zag. The drop in prices has only made goldbugs more faithful, the same way that facts only cause conspiracy theorists to dig in deeper. Sure, gold's value has tanked, but if you can buy it cheaply, all the better, they add. Hope springs eternal. So I wasn&rsquo;t too surprised earlier this week to see Palo Alto-based Merk Investments&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.merkinvestments.com/downloads/2013-12-09-s1-merk-gold-trust.pdf\">announced plans to launch a new gold-backed exchange-traded fund.</a></p> <p>But as BMO Private Bank&rsquo;s Ablin points out, &ldquo;gold has no contractual obligation to come to your rescue in times of trouble.&rdquo; At the height of the financial crisis, the fourth quarter of 2008, stocks in the S&amp;P 500 plunged 22%. Gold did its job, slipping only about 1%. The problem? Treasury bonds were a much better hedge, gaining 14.8% in the same period.&nbsp;</p> <p>As an investor, you can&rsquo;t afford to fall in love with&nbsp;<em>any&nbsp;</em>of your investments. When it comes to a particular asset, like gold, it's time to avoid being a true believer and turn agnostic. Especially given that the likes of Goldman Sachs and UBS&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.cnbc.com/id/101304875\">predicting further big losses in gold this year</a>. You'll want to keep a clear head and not be dazzled by the hint of shiny, easy money.</p>","headline":"The bug of Wall Street: fools' gold","trailText":"Gold never loses its lustre to some believers, but it's a terrible idea to fall in love with any commodity, and especially this one","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3m52z","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/22/1390417226419/2a5cb49e-e86e-4571-a544-51c56358e7ce-140x84.jpeg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/22/1390417226419/2a5cb49e-e86e-4571-a544-51c56358e7ce-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"1","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"427774696","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"52e01030e4b07eba157a7a0b","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Suzanne McGee","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-22T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2031072"