ve of RWE npower has said.</p><p>Paul Massara accused the Labour leader of creating a \"higher political risk\" for energy investors as he ridiculed Miliband's plans on the grounds that 60% of energy prices are set by world commodity markets.</p><p>The head of one of Britain's big six energy firms made his remarks on BBC Radio 4's Today programme after Ofgem criticised npower for publishing a \"misleading\" report, which claimed that energy suppliers made small profits and had little influence on energy bills.</p><p>Massara told the BBC: \"There is no hidden profit. We made a 3.2% margin in our retail business in the first nine months of 2013.\"</p><p>The npower chief executive then turned his fire on Miliband, who electrified the Labour party conference last year by saying that he would impose a 20-month freeze on energy prices until 2017 if he won the next general election.</p><p>Massara told the Today programme of Miliband's price freeze pledge: \"It is already having a dramatic effect. What it is doing is freezing investment. People are looking at the UK and saying: 'Do you know what, if they are freezing prices I am not sure I want to invest in that market place. So what is the risk capital that I have for investing?'</p><p>\"We are seeing a dramatic cooling of investment into the UK because of political uncertainty. As we look at our investment plans – and we know this is true for other people – they are looking at the UK and they are saying: 'Hum, what is the political risk around investing now if we have a price freeze?'</p><p>\"We look at every single investment and we decide where that discretionary capital can go. If deciding where we go we think there is a higher political risk because things have changed then absolutely we make a different decision.</p><p>\"Within npower and within RWE we look at that and we say: 'Is this really where we want to put our additional capital?' That is a question we have and our threshold for investment goes up because there is more political risk. We are not the only one.\"</p><p>Massara said the Miliband pledge would work against the interests of consumers. \"It doesn't help consumers. So yes, it is very attractive, it is a great headline to say 'We want to freeze energy prices'. But what is going to happen afterwards? Ed Miliband cannot control the commodity markets, which set 60% of the price.\"</p><p>The npower chief executive agreed that too much energy is used as a luxury as he cited his teenage daughters who leave on lights, iPods and televisions at home. \"I do think we need to change our approach. We do need to think about energy waste,\" he said.</p>","headline":"Miliband energy price freeze pledge is hitting investment – RWE npower boss","trailText":"Paul Massara accuses Labour leader of creating a 'higher political risk' for energy investors","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3m4b5","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2014/1/22/1390382161724/Paul-Massara-006.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2014/1/22/1390382161724/Paul-Massara-006.jpg","wordcount":"475","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"427706164","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8585339","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Nicholas Watt, chief political correspondent","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-23T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2030567","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-25T09:16:38Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2014/jan/22/miliband-energy-price-freeze-pledge-freezing-investment","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/money/2014/jan/22/miliband-energy-price-freeze-pledge-freezing-investment","tags":[{"id":"money/energy","webTitle":"Energy bills","type":"keyword","sectionId":"money","sectionNam