ney","sectionId":"money","id":"money/2014/jan/12/npower-charging-too-much","fields":{"standfirst":"A series of errors started when we moved house","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-01-12T07:20:42Z","body":"<p><strong>Since moving to a new house in September 2011 we have been subjected to a series of errors from our energy supplier, Npower, which resulted in us being overcharged.</strong></p><p><strong>Prior to moving into the house we requested that Npower change the energy supply from prepay to credit metering on their best available tariff. It refused to make the change until the electricity ran out, which left us without power for 14 hours and then the meter was replaced by another prepay meter. </strong></p><p><strong>When, finally, a credit meter was installed we began to receive excessively high bills. It transpired that Npower had placed us on its highest tariff and it later admitted a mistake. It promised to recalculate our accounts and issue us with a new bill. This was never done. </strong></p><p><strong>We therefore cancelled our direct debit as we had lost confidence in Npower's accounting procedures. We accept that we owe money, but we are unable to accept or trust its assessment of our outstanding debt, when it seems clear that at least on one occasion they have included, as debt, monies already paid by us.  </strong><em>AA, Southampton</em></p><p></p><p>Npower claims that you originally requested that a faulty prepayment metre was replaced and that it only became aware you wanted to be moved to credit metering when the technician arrived at your house. Then it says that since your new account was being processed, it couldn't install the credit meter for another four weeks.</p><p>Bizarrely, it says that after it was installed you were kept on the standard tariff that is the only available option for prepayment customers because you hadn't specifically asked to be on the best tariff. Regardless of whether you did, or not, it's depressing, but unsurprising, that companies don't automatically notify customers they are paying too much.</p><p>After the intervention of the press office Npower has refunded the £339 difference between the standard tariff you were paying and the best one,  plus £50 compensation, but you are still wary of their calculations.</p><p>It's the energy ombudsman who will have to decide who is right.</p><p></p><p><strong>If you need help email Anna Tims at  </strong><a href=\"mailto:your.problems@observer.co.uk\" title=\"\"><strong>your.problems@observer.co.uk</strong></a><strong> or write to Your Problems, The Observer, Kings Place, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Include an address and phone number. </strong></p>","headline":"Npower seems to be charging us too much for our energy","trailText":"A series of errors started when we moved house","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Observer","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3yy72","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/8/1389202699613/Receiving-excessively-hig-001.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/1/8/1389202699613/Receiving-excessively-hig-001.jpg","wordcount":"370","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"426601653","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8531963","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Anna Timms","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-10T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2023166","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-15T07:00:03Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":true},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2014/jan/12/npower-charging-too-much","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/money/2014/jan/12/npower-charging-too-much","tags":[{"id":"money/series/yourproblems","webTitle":"Your problems with Anna Tims","type":"series","sectionId":"money","sectionName":"Money","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/series/yourpr