eremy's own insights. Here is the latest dilemma – what are your thoughts?</p><p></p><p><strong>I have a colleague who constantly distracts me. It is not that he talks to me specifically or particularly loudly, but he constantly sings, puts on babyish voices and mutters under his breath. One really annoying habit is repeating what other people say in a stupid voice: one person may say \"That was a difficult phone call\" and he will mimic them and say \"Difficult oooh yeah!\". Or a colleague on the phone might say \"Goodbye\" and he will put on a stupid voice and say \"Goodbye\" as well. It is constant. When he sings, it is usually the chorus of the same song over and over again for weeks.</strong></p><p></p><p><strong>I have taken him to one side and tactfully said, \"I'm not sure if you realise, but you tend to sing and talk under your breath quite often. A few people have said they find it distracting\". His behaviour stopped for an afternoon but started again the next day. </strong></p><p></p><p><strong>I have asked my manager to move desks and this may happen in a few months, but I will have to deal with this man in the meantime. Also, if I move someone else will have to put up with him, which seems unfair. A lot of other people have complained about him but my manager just shrugs and says \"There is not much I can do about it\".</strong></p><p></p><p><strong>When it gets particularly loud I have mentioned that I really need to focus, but I get a stupid comment in a stupid voice such as \"You are a woman, you should be able to multi-task\". This man is in his 40s.</strong></p><p></p><p>Do you need advice on a work issue? For Jeremy's and readers' help, send a brief email to <a href=\"mailto:dear.jeremy@theguardian.com\" title=\"dear.jeremy@theguardian.com\">dear.jeremy@theguardian.com</a>. Please note that he is unable to answer questions of a legal nature or reply personally.</p>","headline":"What can I do about a singing colleague who distracts me?","trailText